<div id="review_4511035249" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4511035249" />
    <a title="Ed" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4643472-ed"><img alt="Ed" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1324938206p2/4643472.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4511035249?book_show_action=true">Jan 28, 2022</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ed" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ed" href="/user/show/4643472-ed">Ed</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4511035249" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14022886774411129413">I read this book in the 60&apos;s but found it difficult for my teenage mind to comprehend. Rereading it now I can appreciate Merton&apos;s desperate search for God. His faith and budding spiritually eventually pointed him in the direction of Catholicism. As a graduate student at Columbia, he converted to Catholicism but still needed to make a more definitive commitment to his new faith and began thinking seriously about becoming a priest. After earnest conversations with a Priest he knew at Columbia and </span>
  <span id="freeText14022886774411129413" style="display:none">I read this book in the 60's but found it difficult for my teenage mind to comprehend. Rereading it now I can appreciate Merton's desperate search for God. His faith and budding spiritually eventually pointed him in the direction of Catholicism. As a graduate student at Columbia, he converted to Catholicism but still needed to make a more definitive commitment to his new faith and began thinking seriously about becoming a priest. After earnest conversations with a Priest he knew at Columbia and his Franciscan connections at St Bonaventure's College in Olean NY, he committed to enter the Franciscan Monastery as a novitiate but had second thoughts. After much prayer his militant desire to totally commit his life to God lead him to the Trappist Monastery in Gethsemane, Kentucky where he took vows to become a Monk and later a Priest. He spent his days in silence, prayer and contemplation and became one of America's leading Catholic theologians and spiritual authors. Orphaned at 15, I admired his tenacious journey to a life devoted to the service to God and Man. This book was a best seller when it was published in 1948 and is still very much "in print" today. </span>
  <a data-text-id="14022886774411129413" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


