<div id="review_556871270" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/556871270" />
    <a title="Amy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7364659-amy"><img alt="Amy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1429385013p2/7364659.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/556871270?book_show_action=true">Mar 09, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Amy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Amy" href="/user/show/7364659-amy">Amy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7364659-amy?shelf=biography-autobiography">biography-autobiography</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7364659-amy?shelf=spiritual">spiritual</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer556871270" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4961009459225195679">I have known about the Trappist monastery Gethsemani my whole life, having been born not too far from it in Kentucky. Growing up, my beloved grandmother always had a loaf or two of Trappist bread with the stamp of the monastery on the package. It was the best bread I&apos;ve ever tasted, from grains grown and harvested by the monks at Gethsemani. Later on, I found my father reading this biography by one of their own, and I&apos;ve been intrigued by Gethsemani and Merton ever since.<br/><br/>Merton writes in this on</span>
  <span id="freeText4961009459225195679" style="display:none">I have known about the Trappist monastery Gethsemani my whole life, having been born not too far from it in Kentucky. Growing up, my beloved grandmother always had a loaf or two of Trappist bread with the stamp of the monastery on the package. It was the best bread I've ever tasted, from grains grown and harvested by the monks at Gethsemani. Later on, I found my father reading this biography by one of their own, and I've been intrigued by Gethsemani and Merton ever since.<br /><br />Merton writes in this one of his over seventy published books about his early life, conversion to Catholicism, and agonizing decision to join an order. Everyone will approach this book from where s/he is in life; I'm a Unitarian and a social worker, so I see his journey as a near-natural progression: his mother died when he was six, and his father all but abandoned him to pursue his life as a bohemian artist before dying when Merton was fifteen, so this is the story of a boy and young man searching quite literally for a home and family. He finds that solace in the rigors of Catholicism and the monastic order, after finding only unhappiness in the secular world. He alludes to transgressions and unhappiness even keeping him from his original Franciscan affiliation, but does not enumerate precisely what he's done-- the Internet turns up a bit of speculative dirt, but it's hard to say what he's done in the outside world that tortures his conscience for so much of the book, and rather hard to sympathize with him since he does not name it.<br /><br />This book is very, very Catholic, and someone unfamiliar with the liturgical jargon will have a hard time understanding many of the finer points. Catholicism is a high-context religion filled with traditions and rituals, and not knowing many of these, it was hard at times to follow what he was doing and what the meaning may have been. By the end, when he is at Gethsemani, even the dates are feast days rather than calendar dates, which makes it difficult for a non-Catholic reader to know how much time has elapsed.<br /><br />There is much to criticize and much to appreciate here. This was first published in 1948, when he was still a young man and a spiritual neophyte. He went on to fill the next and last 20 years of his life with a great deal of meaning, especially with outreach to other spiritual world leaders of other religions, and I deeply respect the bridges he was able to build between his tradition and others. I wish I had read this years ago; it wasn't too late for me, and if anything piques your interest, it's not too late for anyone to gain from an honest and thorough telling of one man's spiritual journey to find his home.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="4961009459225195679" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


