<div id="review_995444163" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/995444163" />
    <a title="Brigid Hogan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4226648-brigid-hogan"><img alt="Brigid Hogan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1405304486p2/4226648.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/995444163?book_show_action=true">Jul 13, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brigid Hogan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brigid Hogan" href="/user/show/4226648-brigid-hogan">Brigid Hogan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer995444163" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16494986652361932064">This was so hard for me to read, but so worth it. The questions Merton asks himself, especially at the end of the book when he has come into the church and has changed so much of his life, are incredibly challenging questions to turn on myself. I understand that this was written when he was still relatively new to monastic life and that he later regretted some of the more condescending or pietistic passages, but even those passages provide such deep insight into the soul of a young believer - th</span>
  <span id="freeText16494986652361932064" style="display:none">This was so hard for me to read, but so worth it. The questions Merton asks himself, especially at the end of the book when he has come into the church and has changed so much of his life, are incredibly challenging questions to turn on myself. I understand that this was written when he was still relatively new to monastic life and that he later regretted some of the more condescending or pietistic passages, but even those passages provide such deep insight into the soul of a young believer - things that many, many people struggle with in reaction to the excesses of the world.<br /><br />Merton is a challenging figure, and the book reflects that. There are a number of parts where I am left frustrated with the young monk, even when he sees himself as working out the answers he is seeking. I can only imagine how hard it must have been to be his monastic superior. I am even more excited to pick up some of his later work (No man is an island, The Sign of Jonas, New Seeds of Contemplation...) and to really dive into "Contemplative Prayer" which has been on my bookshelf for ages. I am not called to monastic life and don't think I will ever be a contemplative either (though neither did Merton for years!), but I do think there is so much to learn about simplicity, grace, and providence from him.<br /><br />Seven Storey Mountain is a real kick in the pants for a believer - how far is any single person willing to go, how deep into God can a person fall, how willing to listen, to follow, to be open to the action of the Spirit in daily life? Do we get to decide that? Are we open to the idea of serving a purpose here on earth? And how do we find out what that is?<br /><br />And in the words of Jim Martin SJ, "Seeing that someone so human could be holy gives me great hope. Especially with Merton one sees both the sins and the sanctity. And I wonder if this isn't something like the way God sees us."</span>
  <a data-text-id="16494986652361932064" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


