<div id="review_562778706" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/562778706" />
    <a title="Mark Thomas" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4942102-mark-thomas"><img alt="Mark Thomas" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1297127998p2/4942102.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/562778706?book_show_action=true">Mar 16, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mark Thomas" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mark Thomas" href="/user/show/4942102-mark-thomas">Mark Thomas</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer562778706" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15722526928109664333">Disappointed in this work. Part of the Renovare&apos;s &quot;25 Books Every Christian Should Read&quot;. Rambling account of a young man born into a cultured family and of some means. I was stunned when I was halfway into the book that we had only reached the author&apos;s tenth year on the earth.<br/><br/>I anticipated a story that would tell of a true journey of faith. In essence, Merton wanders half-heartedly through a life fairly closed off by higher education, living with inherited means and eventually growing bored wit</span>
  <span id="freeText15722526928109664333" style="display:none">Disappointed in this work. Part of the Renovare's "25 Books Every Christian Should Read". Rambling account of a young man born into a cultured family and of some means. I was stunned when I was halfway into the book that we had only reached the author's tenth year on the earth.<br /><br />I anticipated a story that would tell of a true journey of faith. In essence, Merton wanders half-heartedly through a life fairly closed off by higher education, living with inherited means and eventually growing bored with the banality of a upper middle class life.<br /><br />The ultimate payoff is when Merton decides that he is to become a silent Catholic monk. It is as if when he finally decides to explore a life of faith...it is assumed that Catholicism is the path to take and the man-made traditions of the church are lifted up as the ideal. It is not until near the end of the book that we get some inkling of the author's desire to have a deep spiritual life.<br /><br />Before reading this I had read a small work by Merton entitled "What is Contemplation?" I found that book to be infinitely better than this way too long (462 page) autobiography that struck me as being shallow. <br /><br />I would recommend that one who wanted to get the benefit of Thomas Merton's thinking read "What is Contemplation?'" and pass on this work.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15722526928109664333" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


